'''Joe Falk''' (born January 30, 1951 in [[Chesapeake, Virginia]]) is an American [[auto dealer]] and [[NASCAR]] [[Sprint Cup Series]] team owner, as well as a former [[stock car racing|stock car]] racing driver. He is the owner of the No. 33 car in the Sprint Cup Series, as well as of Little Joe's Autos, an [[automobile dealership]] in the [[Virginia Tidewater]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Joe Falk's first year as a Winston Cup owner has been a bumpy ride|last=Wagner|first=Lon|date=August 9, 1997|work=Virginian-Pilot|page=C1|accessdate=2012-04-20|location=Norfolk, Virginia}}</ref>

==Driving career==
Falk started his racing career at [[Langley Speedway (Virginia)|Langley Speedway]], where he won the track's Late Model championship in 1976;<ref name="Daily1">{{cite web|url=http://articles.dailypress.com/2012-04-02/sports/dp-spt-langley-falk-0403-20120402_1_martinsville-race-nasa-langley-wind-tunnel-champ-kart|title=Joe Falk purchasing No. 33 Cup team|last=O'Brien|first=Marty|date=April 2, 2012|work=Daily Press|location=Newport News, Virginia|accessdate=2012-04-20}}</ref> he was also the winner of what some regard as "the [track's] best Late Model race of all time", in 1983.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.dailypress.com/1997-08-13/sports/9708130001_1_street-stock-races-south-boston-speedway-joe-falk|title=Looking Back: Hanbury Was A Race Chaser If He Had To Be|last=Pearce|first=Al|date=August 13, 1997|work=Daily Press|accessdate=2012-04-20|location=Newport News, Virginia}}</ref>

Falk drove in one NASCAR sanctioned race at the 'national series' level, competing in the [[Busch Series]] (now [[Nationwide Series]]) [[Bobby Isaac Memorial 200]] at [[Hickory Motor Speedway]] in October of 1984; he finished 17th after starting 23rd, driving a Pontiac for Bubba Nissen Racing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.racing-reference.info/rquery?id=falkjo01&trk=t0&series=B|title=Joe Falk's NASCAR Nationwide Series races|year=2012|publisher=Racing-Reference|accessdate=2012-04-20}}</ref>

==Team owner==
===LJ Racing===
[[File:MikeWallace1997Pocono.jpg|thumb|right|The LJ Racing car at [[Pocono Raceway]] in 1997]]
Falk entered NASCAR team ownership in the [[Winston Cup Series]] (now the Sprint Cup Series) in 1997, fielding the No. 91 Chevrolet in a partnership with [[Ron Neal]] under the LJ Racing banner, with driver [[Mike Wallace (racing driver)|Mike Wallace]] and sponsorship from [[Spam]]. The team struggled to make races,<ref>{{cite news|title=Trying to make sirloin out of Spam: Joe Falk determined to succeed in Winston Cup racing|date=May 25, 1997|work=Roanoke Times|pages=B2|accessdate=2012-04-20|location=Roanoke, Virginia}}</ref> and Wallace was released midway through the season;<ref>{{cite news|title=Shifting gears not easy for new owner|last=Pearce|first=Al|date=June 26, 1997|work=Daily Press|page=B1|location=Newport News, Virginia|accessdate=2012-04-20}}</ref> Spam left the team shortly thereafter, and several other drivers drove the car later in the year, with little additional success. [[Kevin Lepage]] joined the team towards the end of the year, and would drive the No. 91 through the first half of 1998 before leaving to join [[Roush Racing]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Lepage to leave Falk for Roush|last=Zeller|first=Bob|date=June 27, 1998|work=Virginian-Pilot|accessdate=2012-04-20|location=Norfolk, Virginia}}</ref> He was replaced by [[Morgan Shepherd]], and then [[Todd Bodine]], who would score the team's best finish, fifth, in the final race of the 1998 season at [[Atlanta Motor Speedway]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Bodine happy with 5th place|date=November 9, 1998|work=Charlotte Observer|page=4B|accessdate=2012-04-20|location=Charlotte, North Carolina}}</ref>

LJ Racing entered the 1999 season with driver [[Steve Grissom]];<ref>{{cite news|title=Grissom happy at LJ Racing|last=Shacklette|first=Buddy|date=February 6, 1999|work=Daytona Beach News-Journal|page=09B|accessdate=2012-04-20|location=Daytona Beach, Florida}}</ref> Grissom was released after failing to qualify for two of the first four races,<ref>{{cite news|title=Grissom seeking <U+2018>right' situation|last=Patterson|first=Ken|date=April 8, 1999|work=Anniston Star|accessdate=2012-04-20|location=Anniston, Alabama}}</ref> being replaced by [[Dick Trickle]], who drove for the team for most of the remainder of the year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Trickle takes over for fired Grissom|date=March 19, 1999|work=Washington Times|accessdate=2012-04-20|location=Washington, D.C.}}</ref> The team would qualify for two races in 2000, at Atlanta and [[Richmond International Raceway|Richmond]] with Todd Bodine driving, before closing down.<ref>{{cite web|title=NASCAR squeezes out small teams|last=Cavin|first=Curt|date=August 3, 2000|work=Indianapolis Star|page=I5|accessdate=2012-04-20|location=Indianapolis, Indiana}}</ref>

===LTD Powersports===
Falk returned to team ownership in the Sprint Cup Series in 2011, running the No. 50 for LTD Powersports with driver [[T.J. Bell]] on a limited basis starting with the [[Southern 500]] at [[Darlington Raceway]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/news/110505/drodman-notebook-darlington-points/index.html|title=Notebook: New point system grows on you|last=Rodman|first=Dave|date=May 5, 2011|work=NASCAR.com|publisher=Turner Sports|accessdate=2012-04-20}}</ref> Bell competed for [[NASCAR Rookie of the Year|Rookie of the Year]] during the season,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoweek.com/article/20110902/NASCAR/110909966/1641/insert%20Volt%20article%20url%20here|title=Andy Lally confirmed as Sprint Cup Rookie of the Year|last=Pearce|first=Al|date=September 2, 2011|work=AutoWeek|accessdate=2012-04-20}}</ref> but only qualified for five races, four of them with Falk's team, which failed to qualify for nine additional races.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/news/120217/mwaltrip-daytona-500/index.html|title=For Waltrip, winning Daytona 500 is everything|last=Rodman|first=Dave|date=February 17, 2012|work=NASCAR.com|publisher=Turner Sports|accessdate=2012-04-20}}</ref>

===Hillman and Childress===
For the 2012 season, Falk joined [[Hillman Racing]], owned by former Cup Series crew chief and [[Germain Racing]] team manager [[Mike Hillman]], as a partial owner; the team attempted to qualify for the [[2012 Daytona 500]] with driver [[Michael Waltrip]],<ref name="Waltrip1">{{cite web|url=http://articles.dailypress.com/2012-02-22/sports/dp-spt-autonotes-0222-20120222_1_langley-title-greg-edwards-trevor-bayne|title=Falk, Waltrip seek Daytona 500 spot|last=O'Brien|first=Marty|date=February 22, 2012|work=Daily Press|accessdate=2012-04-20|location=Newport News, Virginia}}</ref> but failed to make the race.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/columnist/hiestand-tv/story/2012-02-23/hiestand-tv-michael-waltrip/53227068/1|title=Michael Waltrip is a renaissance man|last=Hiestand|first=Michael|date=February 23, 2012|work=USA Today|accessdate=2012-04-20}}</ref> Falk also co-owns Hillman Racing's [[Camping World Truck Series]] team with drivers [[Ward Burton|Ward]] and [[Jeb Burton]]; a second truck for Falk's nephew, [[C. E. Falk]], is hoped to be run later in the season.<ref name="Waltrip1"/>

In April 2012, Falk announced that he was purchasing the No. 33 Sprint Cup Series team from [[Richard Childress Racing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoweek.com/article/20120401/NASCAR/120409999|title=Richard Childress Racing selling one of its four NASCAR Sprint Cup teams|last=Pearce|first=Al|date=April 1, 2012|work=AutoWeek|accessdate=2012-04-20}}</ref> The team, one Childress had planned to run for only the first five races of the season,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.journalnow.com/sports/2012/apr/05/wssport02-rcrs-no-33-gets-more-races-ar-2128078/|title=RCR's No. 33 gets more races|date=April 5, 2012|work=Winston-Salem Journal|accessdate=2012-04-20|location=Winston-Salem, North Carolina}}</ref> was transferred to Falk's ownership after the race at [[Martinsville Speedway]]; Falk planned to run a number of drivers in the car over the remainder of the season, including [[Tony Raines]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoweek.com/article/20120416/NASCAR/120419865|title=Raines a surprise pick for the No. 33 car in Sprint Cup Series|last=Pearce|first=Al|date=April 16, 2012|work=AutoWeek|accessdate=2012-04-20}}</ref> [[Jeff Green (racing driver)|Jeff Green]], [[Austin Dillon]], [[Hermie Sadler|Hermie]] and [[Elliott Sadler]], and C. E. Falk.<ref name="Daily1"/>

